# SafeView — Cursor Master Prompt
# Read every section before writing a single line of code.

---

## 0. Context & Your Role

You are a senior full-stack engineer building **SafeView**, a real-time AI-powered content moderation system. The project is a final-year Software Engineering capstone at Bahir Dar University (Bahir Dar Institute of Technology, Faculty of Computing).

SafeView has **two separate deliverables** that share a common FastAPI AI backend:

| Deliverable | Platform | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| **Browser Extension** | Chrome/Chromium (desktop) | Detects video elements on any web page and blurs the full video when restricted content is found |
| **Android App** | Android 10+ (Flutter) | (a) In-app browser that filters web video, AND (b) Screen-capture overlay that blurs third-party apps (YouTube, TikTok, etc.) system-wide |

The reference design is the RAD/RDD on file. **Section 2 of this prompt overrides anything in those documents.** When in doubt, this prompt wins.

---

## 1. Project Scope

### 1.1 Shared AI Backend (FastAPI + PyTorch)

One backend serves both the extension and the Android app.

- **Nudity detection** → powered by `dino_v3_linear.pth`, a custom-trained model the team provides. Cursor's job is only to **load the weights and run inference correctly** — do not attempt to train, modify, or replace this model.
- **All other categories** (Violence, Kissing/Romantic, Profanity, LGBTQ+ Symbols) → **stub implementations** that always return `{ detected: false, confidence: 0.0 }`. Each stub must be clearly marked `# TODO: replace with real model` and must implement the same interface as the nudity module so swapping is trivial later.

### 1.2 Browser Extension (Chrome MV3)

**In scope:**
- Detect every `<video>` element on any tab (including common player wrappers on YouTube, TikTok web, Netflix, etc.)
- Sample frames at ≤ 2 FPS (500 ms gate)
- Send frames to the local FastAPI backend for inference
- On detection: apply `filter: blur(24px)` to the **entire `<video>` element** — no coordinate-based masking
- Remove blur when detection clears
- Audio monitoring stub: scan `<track>` subtitles for profanity → `video.muted = true` for 1.5 s
- Metadata filter stub: TMDb lookup, always returns ALLOW until API key is configured
- Popup UI: protection toggle, status indicator, link to options
- Options page: per-category toggles, sensitivity slider (Low/Medium/High), backend URL field, profanity word list editor

**Out of scope for the extension:**
- Surgical / coordinate-based masking
- iOS support
- Any cloud AI API calls
- Any remote data storage

### 1.3 Android App (Flutter)

**In scope:**

**A. In-App Browser (WebView-based)**
- A Flutter WebView that loads any URL the user types
- Intercepts rendered video frames via a JavaScript bridge injected into the WebView
- Sends frames to the FastAPI backend (same endpoint as the extension)
- On detection: calls back into Flutter to apply a full-screen blur overlay (`BackdropFilter` widget) over the entire WebView
- Removes the overlay when detection clears
- Works without any special OS permissions beyond internet access

**B. Screen Capture Overlay (System-Wide)**
- Uses `MediaProjection` API to capture the screen at ≤ 2 FPS
- Frames are sent to the FastAPI backend for inference
- On detection: draws a `WindowManager` full-screen overlay (a solid dark layer or heavy blur effect) over whatever app is in the foreground
- Requires the user to grant:
  - `FOREGROUND_SERVICE` permission
  - `SYSTEM_ALERT_WINDOW` ("Display over other apps") permission
  - MediaProjection runtime consent dialog
- The overlay service runs as a foreground service with a persistent notification
- Overlay is removed when detection clears or user taps the notification to stop

**C. Shared App Features**
- Dashboard: protection ON/OFF toggle, active mode indicator (browser vs overlay), live status feed
- Settings: per-category filter toggles, sensitivity slider, backend URL configuration
- All settings persisted in `SharedPreferences`
- Privacy: captured frames live only in RAM; never written to disk or sent anywhere except `localhost`

**Out of scope for Android:**
- iOS build
- Surgical masking (always full-screen blur/overlay)
- Cloud inference
- Root-level hooks or accessibility service hacks beyond standard `MediaProjection`

